high fat diet mouse model, memory formation was impaired and
treatment with exendin-4 reversed this [60]. Exendin-4 also protected
streptozotocin (STZ)-induced diabetic rats from learning impairments
as demonstrated using an elevated plus maze task and passive avoid-
ance task [61]. Treatment with native GLP-1 also protected memory
formation in STZ-treated rats [62]. Liraglutide protected STZ treated
rats from impairments of learning a water maze task and a passive
avoidance task, and improved motor impairments observed in the
forced swimming test, open ﬁeld, elevated plus maze, and rotarod
motor coordination tests [63]. Liraglutide also normalized object re-
cognition memory impairments in mice were maintained on a high fat
diet [64]. Furthermore, the DPP-4 inhibitor Sitagliptin, which elevates
GLP-1
concentrations
